<P><HI>Ignorantia Scientifica.</HI></P>
<P>A brief ESSAY ON <HI>Mans not knowing his</HI> TIME: THE Ju&s;t INFERENCES from it, AND THE Great ADVANTAGES of it. Upon a Special and Mournful Occa&s;ion.</P>
<Q><BIBL>P&s;al. xc. 12.</BIBL>
<P><HI>So teach us to Number our Days.</HI></P></Q>
<L><HI>Fieres &s;i &s;cires unum tua tempora Men&s;em;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Rides, quum non &s;int for&s;itan una Dies?</HI></L>
<P>In <HI>Engli&s;h.</HI></P>
<L>T'would make thee &s;erious, did&s;t thou &s;urely know,</L>
<L>Down to the Grave thou in a <HI>Month</HI> mu&s;t go:</L>
<L>Why to vain Mirth a loo&s;e then can&s;t thou give,</L>
<L>Not knowing that thou ha&s;t a <HI>Day</HI> to live?</L>
<P><HI>BOSTON</HI> in <HI>NE</HI> Printed by <HI>B. Green,</HI> for <HI>Samuel Gerri&s;h,</HI> the lower End of Corn-hill, 1727.</P>
