<PB N="1" REF="002913_0003_0FE694AB97D188C0">
<HEAD>INSTRUCTION Fetch'd from IGNORANCE.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">On the Sudden DEATH of a Young Gentleman. <HI>Jan.</HI> 14.1726, 7.</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q><BIBL><HI>Eccl. IX. 12.</HI></BIBL>
<P>Man knoweth not his Time.&mdash;</P></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P>AND therefore there is no Man in the Auditory <HI>at this Time,</HI> who <HI>knows</HI> any other but that <HI>This</HI> may be the <HI>La&s;t Time</HI> of his being here; For ought that any One <HI>knows,</HI> This may be the <HI>La&s;t Sabbath</HI> he &s;hall have &s;hining on him; This the <HI>La&s;t Sermon</HI> he &s;hall have &s;peaking to him. Certainly <HI>This alone</HI> may be enough to be&s;peak from us, a Great Attention to what we have now before us.</P>
<P><HI>Man knoweth not is Time.]</HI> The Text is capa|ble to have a Lively, yea, a Daily <HI>Paraphra&s;e</HI> made upon it.&mdash;What think you of &s;uch a <HI>Pa|raphra&s;e</HI> as This? &mdash;</P>
<PB N="2" REF="002913_0004_0FE694ABB1D508C8">
<P>&mdash;A Young Gentleman,<NOTE N="*">Mr. SAMUEL HIRST.</NOTE> De&s;cended of wor|thy <HI>Progenitors;</HI> Accompli&s;hed with the Advantages of a Liberal as well as Religious <HI>Education;</HI> Recommended unto the <HI>Loves</HI> &amp; <HI>Hopes</HI> of his Friends by many De&s;ireable circum|&s;tances; After very little more than <HI>Three Times Seven Years</HI> of Appearance in the World; Be to all Apprehen&s;ion in perfect Health; in the mid&s;t of Bu&s;ine&s;s, and of Company;&mdash; And &mdash; But here the Story Stops! &mdash; <HI>At once</HI> to fall down <HI>Dead</HI> in the Street! &mdash; The Mounting &amp; Glowing <HI>Spark,</HI> in a Moment go out, and fall down into the com|mon Heap of A&s;hes! &mdash; This is a <HI>Paraphra&s;e,</HI> which the Great GOD has ju&s;t now given us, on, <HI>Man knows not his Time.</HI> An affecting Pa|raphra&s;e! <HI>Go to now, ye that &s;ay, To Morrow we will do this or that! ye know not what &s;hall be on the Morrow. What is your Life? It is even a vapour that appears for a little time, and then vani&s;hes away.</HI></P>
<P>BUT the matter mu&s;t be further look'd into.</P>
<P>MY Text is found in a Book Entituled, <HI>The Preacher.</HI> It &s;eems, the Things which are in this Book in&s;i&s;ted on, are &s;uch as it well becomes a <HI>Preacher</HI> to in&s;i&s;t upon. We have here the <HI>Re|tractations</HI> of a <HI>Solomon,</HI> writing a Treati&s;e upon, <HI>The Chief End of Man;</HI> An Aged <HI>Solomon,</HI> after much Experience, confe&s;&s;ing his own Errors, and correcting of ours, upon that Important Subject. The Word which we render, <HI>The Preacher,</HI> carries in it &s;ome Intimations of, <HI>A Soul upon Recollection.</HI> We have here that Enquiry managed, <HI>What is
<PB N="3" REF="002913_0005_0FE694E08B3A67A8">true Happine&s;s?</HI> And, <HI>How,</HI> or <HI>Where,</HI> is <HI>true Hap|pine&s;s</HI> is to be met withal! Upon a Serious <HI>Re|collection,</HI> it is here pronounced, That our <HI>Tem|poral Happine&s;s</HI> is to <HI>Enjoy Chearfully</HI> what we <HI>Po&s;&s;e&s;s Hone&s;tly.</HI> But, Wo to that Man, who Stops here; who is put off &s;o; who knows none but a <HI>Temporal Happine&s;s.</HI> There is an <HI>Eternal Happine&s;s,</HI> which a Man ought always and chiefly to be concern'd about : An <HI>Happine&s;s</HI> to be found in the Day when <HI>G O D &s;hall bring every work into Judgment.</HI> And the way to obtain this <HI>Happine&s;s</HI> is for a Man to <HI>Fear G O D and keep His Commandments.</HI> In the pro&s;ecution of the&s;e things, very pertinent are the Remarks made in this Book, upon the Di|ver&s;e <HI>Vanities,</HI> whereof Men do in this Life un|dergo the grievous <HI>Vexations.</HI> One of tho&s;e Di|ver&s;e <HI>Vanities,</HI> is Remark'd in the Text before us; <HI>Man knoweth not his Time.</HI> It refers to &s;uch occurrences, as the preceeding Ver&s;e takes notice of. <HI>Time</HI> intends the <HI>Changes</HI> which befalls us in <HI>Time;</HI> The <HI>Changes</HI> which are al&s;o called <HI>Chances,</HI> becau&s;e we &s;ee not the Cau&s;es of them. The <HI>Rea&s;ons</HI> as well as the <HI>Sea&s;ons</HI> are &s;ecret unto us. But above all, <HI>Time</HI> intends the end of our <HI>Time.</HI> It is our <HI>Death</HI> which is our <HI>Time :</HI> The <HI>Time</HI> wherein we are to <HI>Dy,</HI> and we are to have no more <HI>Time</HI> allow'd unto us. The un|certainty of this <HI>Time,</HI> wherein it plea&s;es the Holy <HI>Lord of Time,</HI> who <HI>Inhabits Eternity</HI> to keep us, has here &s;ome elegant Illu&s;trations and Re|&s;emblances. The <HI>Fi&s;h</HI> Knows not the <HI>Time</HI> of its being taken in the <HI>Nett.</HI> The <HI>Bird</HI> knows not
<PB N="4" REF="002913_0006_0FE694ADECB7C8D0">the <HI>Time</HI> of its being taken in the <HI>Snare;</HI> So are Men <HI>Suddenly</HI> taken by the <HI>Evil-Time</HI> of a <HI>Dying Hour.</HI> The <HI>Netts</HI> of <HI>Death</HI> are &s;pread for us. The <HI>Snares</HI> of <HI>Death</HI> are laid for us. <HI>Man knows not the Time</HI> of his being taken in them.</P>
<P>ATTEND unto a DOCTRINE of an Im|portance as U&s;eful as Awful, to be at <HI>all Times</HI> thought upon.</P>
<P><HI>LITTLE do People know the Times that are hereafter to pa&s;s over them : Little do we know what Changes are to come, and when they are to come upon us.</HI></P>
<P><HI>CONTINGENCIES</HI> are Things which we cannot have a <HI>certain knowledge</HI> of. Tis at be&s;t, but an <HI>Opinion,</HI> tis at be&s;t but a <HI>Conjecture,</HI> that we can have of them. Now, with re&s;pect unto <HI>us,</HI> what are all <HI>Futurities,</HI> but <HI>Contingencies.</HI></P>
<P>MY DOCTRINE is a String which the Quill of <HI>Solomon</HI> did very much harp upon. And mo&s;t certainly the <HI>Wi&s;dom</HI> of a <HI>Solomon</HI> could not be expre&s;s'd without Strong Impre&s;&s;ions from &s;uch a Meditation. Tis bewailed by <HI>Solomon</HI> as the <HI>Mi&s;ery of Man,</HI> Eccl. VIII. 7. <HI>He knoweth not that which &s;hall be; For who can tell him when it &s;hall be!</HI> Oh! may we have the <HI>Wi&s;dom</HI> to make our <HI>Advantage</HI> of this <HI>Mi&s;ery;</HI> &s;ince we do know what we have to do, that we may be pre|pared for <HI>that which &s;hall be.</HI></P>
<P>THIS, This is the Tendency of the Meditation upon which we are now proceeding.</P>
<PB N="5" REF="002913_0007_0FE694E68926F8C8">
<P>WE will Inquire, Fir&s;t, <HI>What is there in the Times pa&s;&s;ing over us, which we mu&s;t not have the Fore-knowledge of?</HI></P>
<P>TWO words will fully eno' expre&s;s the matter.</P>
<P>Fir&s;t LITTLE do we <HI>Fore-know</HI> the <HI>Quantity</HI> of our <HI>Time;</HI> or what will be the <HI>Duration</HI> of it. <HI>Man knoweth not his Time;</HI> in that he <HI>knows not,</HI> whether it will be a <HI>Longer Time,</HI> or a <HI>Shorter Time.</HI> As it has been &s;aid, <HI>What man is he that liveth, and &s;hall not &s;ee Death?</HI> So it may be &s;aid, <HI>What man alive is there, who knows when he &s;hall &s;ee Death?</HI> We are told, <HI>The living know that they &s;hall Dy.</HI> But which of the <HI>Living</HI> are they who <HI>know when they are to Dye?</HI> The <HI>Pre&s;a|ges</HI> that &s;ome few have had of their <HI>Time,</HI> are extraordinary! One &s;aid, Gen XXVII. 2. <HI>I am old, I know not the Day of my Death.</HI> And the <HI>Young</HI> does as little <HI>know the Day of his Death.</HI> It is an ancient &s;aying, <HI>If an old Man has Death &s;tanding before his Face, a young Man has Death &s;tanding behind his Back.</HI> The <HI>Time</HI> of its giving the <HI>Fatal &s;troke,</HI> is as little known to the one, as to the other. <HI>One that is in his full &s;trength, being wholly at ea&s;e and quiet, and having his Bones moi&s;tned with morrow;</HI> Even &s;uch an one does <HI>not know his Time;</HI> for even &s;uch an one may <HI>Dy</HI> at <HI>this</HI> very <HI>Time. One that is in Bitterne&s;s of Soul, and never Eats with plea&s;ure,</HI> becau&s;e of the Infirmities under what he langui&s;hes; even &s;uch an one al&s;o does <HI>not know his Time.</HI> For even &s;uch an one may be Repriev'd from <HI>Death</HI> beyond expectation; and &s;ee many <HI>Stronger</HI> ones <HI>ly down in the Du&s;t</HI> before him. We do all know, That <HI>it
<PB N="6" REF="002913_0008_0FE694AE521958B8">is appointed unto man once to dy.</HI> But which of us does <HI>know his appointed Time</HI> for it; or when he is to <HI>Dy?</HI> Ordinarily, <HI>of that Day &amp; Hour knoweth no Man.</HI></P>
<P>Secondly, LITTLE do we <HI>Foreknow</HI> the <HI>Qua|lity</HI> of our <HI>Time;</HI> or what we are to <HI>Encounter</HI> in it. Shall we have a <HI>Good Time,</HI> or a <HI>Bad Time</HI> of it? <HI>Man knoweth not!</HI> In our <HI>Time</HI> &s;hall we &s;ee Days of <HI>Plea&s;ure,</HI> or Days of <HI>Sorrow? Man know|eth not!</HI> Shall we have our <HI>Time</HI> &s;weetned with much <HI>Pro&s;perity,</HI> or embittered with much <HI>Ad|ver&s;ity? Man knoweth not!</HI> The World may not prove either &s;o <HI>Good</HI> as we <HI>hope,</HI> or &s;o <HI>Bad</HI> as we <HI>fear?</HI> 'Tis mo&s;t commonly &s;o. Some look for a <HI>&s;adder Time</HI> than ever does arrive unto them. So did the <HI>I&s;raeliti&s;h</HI> Hero, when he &s;aid, <HI>I &s;hall one day peri&s;h by the hand of Saul.</HI> But much oft|ner do Men look for a <HI>better Time,</HI> than what anon comes unto them. They &s;ay, <HI>I &s;hall never be moved;</HI> But, GOD <HI>hides His Face, and they are Troubled.</HI> When <HI>Jo&s;eph</HI> was a Pri&s;oner and his <HI>Foot they did humble with the affliction of a chain; The Iron, that did penetrate into his very Soul:</HI> Did he <HI>know</HI> what was to be done for him, when the King <HI>constituted him to be the Ruler of his Hou&s;e; yea, and the Governour of all that was po&s;&s;e&s;s'd by him.</HI> When <HI>Haman</HI> was in all the Grandeur of the <HI>Per&s;ion</HI> Court, and the chief Mi|ni&s;ter of State there; Did he <HI>know</HI> how near he and his Family were, to a matchle&s;s confu&s;ion? What <HI>Accidents</HI> we are to meet withal, whether <HI>Joyful</HI> Accidents, or <HI>Woful</HI> Accidents, we mu&s;t not <HI>know,</HI> indeed &s;o much as one day before hand.
<PB N="7" REF="002913_0009_0FE694E6A31A2908">So we are admoni&s;hed; Prov. XXVII. 1. <HI>Thou knowe&s;t not what a Day may bring forth.</HI> O Man, Thou <HI>knowe&s;t not,</HI> what may <HI>This Day</HI> befall thee in thy Per&s;on, in thy Family, in thy Intere&s;t. Thou <HI>knowest not</HI> what may be the <HI>Tidings</HI> that will <HI>This Day</HI> be brought unto thee. Thou <HI>know|e&s;t not</HI> in the <HI>Evening</HI> what may befall thee be|fore the <HI>Morning,</HI> or in the <HI>Morning</HI> what &s;hall befall thee before the <HI>Evening;</HI> Any more than the Men upon whom the <HI>Tower of Siloam fell,</HI> that the <HI>Tower</HI> was to fall, while they were un|der it.</P>
<P>THE Articles wherein you have had &s;et be|fore you, the <HI>Future Events</HI> of our <HI>Times,</HI> where|of our GOD will keep us in the greate&s;t <HI>Uncer|tainties,</HI> are then the&s;e Two; Fir&s;t, That which is the greate&s;t of all our <HI>Changes;</HI> And, then, all the <HI>Changes</HI> which may before That come up|on us. Our Meditation mu&s;t not ea&s;ily, and pre|&s;ently di&s;mi&s;s the&s;e Articles of our <HI>Times</HI> which are <HI>unknown</HI> unto us. But before we pa&s;s any further, Let an earne&s;t EXHORTATION pre|vail with us, To <HI>Entertain this Meditation, and he duely affected with it.</HI> Oh! may this Thought be often rolling in our Minds; <HI>I know not my Time, nor do I know any thing that is to befal me in my Time!</HI> And may our Minds feel the power of it; bring our Lives under the power of it! The very <HI>Pagans</HI> would &s;ometimes give an Entertain|ment unto this Meditation; and &s;ay, <HI>Ne&s;cis quid &s;erus Ve&s;per vebat;</HI> O Man, Thou knowe&s;t not what may before Night be to come upon thee. Certainly, It becomes <HI>Chri&s;tians</HI> to give a more
<PB N="8" REF="002913_0010_0FE694B7265998B0">affecting entertainment unto &s;uch a Meditation.</P>
<P>Fir&s;t; THE ca&s;e of <HI>Mortality</HI> is above all to be thus con&s;idered; That <HI>Man knows not his Time,</HI> when his <HI>Mortality</HI> mu&s;t have the Opera|tion of it fini&s;hed. Man lies under a <HI>Sentence</HI> of <HI>Death;</HI> and the <HI>Time</HI> for <HI>Execution</HI> is <HI>determined</HI> with GOD; <HI>Lord, The number of our Months is with thee; Thou ha&s;t appointed our Bounds, that we cannot pa&s;s.</HI> But Man mu&s;t not <HI>know the Time,</HI> until the Executioner come and bring the Bow-&s;tring. There is no <HI>Day</HI> that breaks upon any Man, but for ought he <HI>knows, His Time is come, and the Day of his Death. Sudden Deaths</HI> are &s;ome of tho&s;e Things, whereto all Men living are expo&s;ed. We find it &s;uppo&s;ed, Numb VI. 9. <HI>A man may die very &s;uddenly.</HI> 'Tis what we &s;ee fulfill'd on great <HI>Numbers;</HI> We need not for the proof of it quote the Book of <HI>Numbers.</HI> The commi&s;&s;ions which our glotious GOD gives to the <HI>Angel of Death</HI> are often kept &s;ecret until the very Day, that he comes and &s;wears unto them, <HI>No more Time</HI> &s;hall be given them. It may be the Portion of <HI>Wicked Men</HI> to <HI>Dy &s;uddenly.</HI> The profane Men, who can &s;ay of the Thing they never once thought upon, <HI>They thought no more of it than of their Dying Day;</HI> find it according to their word; Their <HI>Dying Day</HI> comes at a <HI>Time</HI> which they <HI>thought not</HI> of. The Men of <HI>Sodom;</HI> Did they <HI>know their Time?</HI> A bright fair, Sun|&s;hiny Morning, found them wallowing in all Im|purities; Before Night the <HI>Vengeance of Eternal Fire</HI> came down upon them. The <HI>Egyptians;</HI> Did they <HI>know their Time?</HI> In the Morning
<PB N="9" REF="002913_0011_0FE694E8F06FA880">they were full of brave Expectations to divide <HI>Spoils</HI> and <HI>Slaves</HI> among them, and to do won|drous Exploits. That Night they were Drown'd, and Damn'd; the <HI>Sea covered them.</HI> The <HI>Phi|listines;</HI> Did they <HI>know their Time?</HI> In the Morning they had nothing in their Eye, but the <HI>Sports</HI> of an Holiday. E're the Night came, they were cru&s;h'd all to pieces. <HI>Ananias &amp; Sapphira;</HI> Did they <HI>know their Time.</HI> They came out well to the Meeting, and they are carried home Dead! It may be the Portion of <HI>Godly Men</HI> al&s;o to <HI>Dy &s;uddenly.</HI> It may be a Privilege granted by GOD unto &s;ome of His mo&s;t Favoured ones, to <HI>Dy</HI> &s;uch a <HI>Death. Uzzah,</HI> Did he <HI>know his Time;</HI> In the Morning of the Day, when the <HI>Ark</HI> was to be carried into the City of <HI>David?</HI> or, The Prophet &s;ent unto <HI>Jeroboam;</HI> Did he <HI>know his Time,</HI> in the Morning of the Day when the <HI>Lion</HI> fell upon him? Others le&s;s obnoxious find it &s;o.</P>
<P>Yea, Secondly; THE Ca&s;e of every <HI>Calamity</HI> is thus to be con&s;idered. <HI>Man knows not his Time,</HI> when that <HI>Calamity</HI> will befal him, wherein GOD will <HI>perform the Thing that is appointed for him.</HI> One that has an <HI>Husband,</HI> or a <HI>Father,</HI> in the Morn|ing, does not <HI>know,</HI> but before Night, the &s;tate of a <HI>Widow,</HI> or an <HI>Orphan</HI> may be Theirs: The <HI>Sun</HI> may <HI>&s;et at Noon</HI> with us, and leave us in a <HI>Sud|den Darkne&s;s.</HI> A <HI>Job</HI> has his <HI>Hou&s;e</HI> full of <HI>Chil|dren</HI> in the Morning; but he does not know that before Night, he &s;hall have neither <HI>Hou&s;e</HI> nor <HI>Children</HI> left unto him. In this evil World, every Man knows, that his Dependence may be like that of the Apo&s;tles, <HI>Afflictions wait for me:</HI> But
<PB N="10" REF="002913_0012_0FE694B7460100A8">then he mu&s;t add like the Apo&s;tle. Act. XX. 22. <HI>Not knowing the Things that &s;hall befal me.</HI> And much more, <HI>Not knowing the Time when they &s;hall befal me.</HI></P>
<P>IT was counted a Flight of Wi&s;dom; <HI>All that I know, is that I know nothing!</HI> It will be wi&s;ely done of us to make the <HI>knowledge</HI> of our <HI>Igno|rance</HI> in this point, as efficacious as may be upon us; <HI>This I know, that man knoweth not his Time.</HI></P>
<P>WE will enquire, Secondly; <HI>Whence is it, that we mu&s;t not have the Fore-knowledge of the Times that are to pa&s;s over us?</HI></P>
<P>Now, Fir&s;t; THERE is for it, the <HI>Fir&s;t Rea&s;on</HI> of all things; the grand <HI>Rea&s;on of all Rea&s;ons.</HI> The <HI>Sovereign will</HI> of GOD; That is <HI>Rea&s;on</HI> enough. The <HI>Sovereignty</HI> of the Great GOD will be maintained in it. It was a ju&s;t Acknow|ledgment; P&s;al. XXXI. 15. <HI>O Lord, my Times are in thy Hand.</HI> It was a ju&s;t Admonition; Act. I. 7. <HI>It is not for you to know the Times, which the Father has put in His own power.</HI> All that &s;hall befall us in our <HI>Times,</HI> is Decreed by the GOD that made us. Now, the <HI>Decree</HI> is by our So|vereign kept a <HI>Secret:</HI> For <HI>&s;uch is His will and plea&s;ure,</HI> that it &s;hould be &s;o. There is a Glori|ous One, who is in our Tran&s;lation of the Bible, called, <HI>The Ancient of Days.</HI> The Original is, <HI>The Appointer of Times.</HI> 'Tis fit, that our <HI>Times</HI> remain <HI>unknown</HI> to any but Him that has the <HI>Appointing</HI> of the <HI>Times.</HI></P>
<P>BUT, there is more than this to be &s;aid of the matter.</P>
<PB N="11" REF="002913_0013_0FE694E9114DDAF8">
<P>Fir&s;t, IT is from the <HI>Pitty</HI> and <HI>Mercy</HI> of our Gracious GOD unto the poor Children of Men, that they mu&s;t not <HI>know their Time,</HI> nor what is to befall them in their <HI>Time.</HI></P>
<P>IT may well be a&s;cribed unto the <HI>Pitty</HI> of our GOD, That we do <HI>not know our Time;</HI> For &s;uch <HI>a knowledge</HI> would very much de&s;troy the <HI>comfort</HI> of our <HI>Time;</HI> very much make for us a mo&s;t un|comfortable <HI>Time,</HI> Here, Here, mo&s;t emphati|cally; <HI>He that increa&s;eth Knowledge increa&s;eth Sorrow.</HI> It would mightily take away the <HI>com|fort</HI> which we take in any thing under the Sun, if we knew aforehand, <HI>When</HI> and <HI>How</HI> we are to take our leave of that <HI>comfort.</HI> It is reported concerning <HI>Eli&s;ha,</HI> 2 King. VIII. 11, 12. <HI>The man of God wept; And Hazael &s;aid, Why weepeth my Lord? And he an&s;wered, Becau&s;e I know the evil, that thou wilt do.</HI> Thus, If a Man <HI>know the evil Time</HI> that is to befall him&s;elf, or his Hou&s;e, and the <HI>Time</HI> of the <HI>Evil,</HI> he would fall a <HI>weeping</HI> at it; into &s;uch a <HI>weeping,</HI> that he would be able to find little Reli&s;h in the gifts of GOD unto him. The <HI>Anticipations</HI> of <HI>Trouble</HI> would break the Hearts of Men, if they knew before hand all the <HI>Trouble</HI> that is to come upon them, and the <HI>Time</HI> when it will come. Our Lord has told us; Math. VI. 34. <HI>Sufficient unto the Day is the evil thereof.</HI> It will be &s;oon enough to <HI>know the evil,</HI> when the <HI>Day</HI> comes. If we &s;hould <HI>know the evil</HI> before the <HI>Day,</HI> it would multiply exceedingly, &amp; keep growing &amp; growing, and &s;calding upon us; we &s;hould be more &s;calded before it falls, than we &s;hould be in the Actual Falling of it. It is a mo&s;t
<PB N="12" REF="002913_0014_0FE694B864725280">con&s;picuous Difference between a <HI>Man,</HI> &amp; a <HI>Bruit.</HI> And I look upon it, as no de&s;picable Argument, that <HI>Man</HI> is made for a World that is <HI>to come.</HI> A <HI>Man</HI> has a &s;trong Apprehen&s;ion of what is <HI>to come :</HI> And what he <HI>knows</HI> is <HI>to come,</HI> he feels it Exqui&s;itely, he feels it Wonderfully. Oh! Should many a Man <HI>know, At &s;uch a Time, &s;hall my Hou&s;e be laid in A&s;hes;</HI> Or, <HI>At &s;uch a Time, a Relative that is the De&s;ire of my Eyes will be taken from me:</HI> Or, <HI>at &s;uch a Time I &s;hall my &s;elf be carried unto my long Home, and the Mourners for me &s;hall walk about the Streets;</HI> Verily, this <HI>knowledge</HI> would cau&s;e an un&s;peaka|ble Angui&s;h in him. Such a <HI>knowledge</HI> of our <HI>Time,</HI> would cau&s;e a cry to be heard among us, like that which was once heard in <HI>Aegypt;</HI> A cry whereof they kept an Anniver&s;ary comme|moration among them, for many Ages.</P>
<P>Again; IT may be a&s;cribed unto the <HI>Mercy</HI> of GOD, that we do <HI>not know our Time.</HI> For, hereby we come the better to <HI>Know</HI> and to <HI>Do,</HI> the <HI>Duty</HI> of our <HI>Time.</HI> Here is indeed an <HI>Igno|rance,</HI> that is very truly, and very ju&s;tly, the <HI>Mother of Devotion.</HI> Our <HI>not knowing our Time,</HI> and the Things to come, does train us up, to a <HI>Filial Faith</HI> in the <HI>Fatherly Care,</HI> of the Lord, who only has all tho&s;e Things in His own Hands. We read; Jam. IV. 14, 15. <HI>Ye know not what &s;hall be on the Morrow;&mdash;Ye ought to &s;ay, If the Lord will, we &s;hall live, and do this or that.</HI> We Refer our &s;elves to the <HI>Will of GOD,</HI> with the more of <HI>Re&s;ignation;</HI> a mo&s;t humble and lovely <HI>Re&s;ignation;</HI> becau&s;e we <HI>know not what &s;hall be on
<PB N="13" REF="002913_0015_0FE694F3F14C3188">the Morrow.</HI> And our <HI>Preparation,</HI> a Watchful and Prayerful <HI>Preparation</HI> for the wor&s;t that may happen to us; This is promoted by our <HI>not knowing our Time,</HI> and what &s;hall happen to us. It is pre&s;&s;ed upon us; Mar. XIII. 33. <HI>Take heed, watch, and pray; for ye know not when the Time is.</HI> Becau&s;e we <HI>know not the Time,</HI> when we or ours are to Dy, or what is to befall us; If this won't put us upon <HI>Watching</HI> and <HI>Praying,</HI> and keep us in a way of Holy walking, I don't know what will! <HI>I know not my Time, nor what I am to &s;ee in a very Little Time.</HI> A Man of any &s;en&s;e will think &s;o. But Methinks, One that has the lea&s;t grain of &s;en&s;e, mu&s;t go on to think; <HI>I de&s;ire now to keep alive the con&s;tant Fear of GOD, all the Time that He &s;hall allow me; I de|&s;ire to be armed with Patience and Submi&s;&s;ion, for all the unea&s;y Things which in my Remaining Time I may find re&s;erved for me.</HI> Sirs, we mu&s;t yield a <HI>Blindfold Obedience</HI> unto GOD; This <HI>Blindfold Obedience</HI> is a <HI>Well aim'd Obedience.</HI></P>
<P>Secondly. THERE is a Dreadful <HI>Judgment</HI> of GOD, upon <HI>Wicked Men</HI> in it, that they mu&s;t not <HI>know their Time.</HI> The wrath of GOD upon <HI>Wicked Men</HI> mu&s;t overtake them. After what manner mu&s;t it overtake them? We read; P&s;al. XI. 6. <HI>Upon the wicked He &s;hall rain &s;nares&mdash; and an horrible tempe&s;t,</HI> We read; P&s;al. LXXIII. 18, 19. <HI>Surely, Thou ha&s;t &s;et them in &s;lippery places; &mdash; How are they brought into De&s;olation, as in a Moment?</HI> Of the Wicked Man, we are told; P&s;al. XXXVII. 13. <HI>The Lord &s;hall laugh at him, for He &s;ees that his Day is coming.</HI> Why;
<PB N="14" REF="002913_0016_0FE694B8847C21E0">The Man does <HI>not &s;ee</HI> it him&s;elf! This gives a greater Triumph to the <HI>Ju&s;tice</HI> of GOD, in the <HI>Day</HI> that comes upon him. The Vengeance of GOD upon a wicked Man, mu&s;t come <HI>Irre&s;i&s;tibly.</HI> It comes <HI>at once,</HI> and that makes it the more <HI>Irre&s;i&s;tible.</HI> A <HI>Whirlwind</HI> of <HI>Wrath</HI> mu&s;t come upon a wicked Man. A <HI>Whirlwind,</HI> that mu&s;t ri&s;e <HI>at once.</HI> It mu&s;t gather <HI>Suddenly,</HI> It mu&s;t be big with terrible <HI>Thunder.</HI> It mu&s;t break him to pieces, before he has any <HI>Time</HI> to look about him. He mu&s;t <HI>not know his Time.</HI> No; He mu&s;t be <HI>Surprized</HI> by the Vengeance of GOD.</P>
<P>BUT now, Let us make our more particular Improvement of the&s;e Faithful &s;ayings.</P>
<P N="1"><HI>I.</HI> SINCE our GOD will not let us <HI>know our Time,</HI> we mu&s;t beware of <HI>curious Inquiries</HI> after the Future Events of our <HI>Time.</HI> There is a certain Prerogative, of which <HI>Vain Man that would be wi&s;e,</HI> is very ambitious; That is, that <HI>Prerogative</HI> of <HI>Divination:</HI> Men would fain <HI>know their Time,</HI> and what is to come hereafter. And, how many cur&s;ed Arts of <HI>Divination</HI> have been invented for the gratification of this <HI>Curi|o&s;ity!</HI> But, O vain Man, Thou lifte&s;t up thy hand unto a Forbidden <HI>Tree of Knowledge,</HI> when thou art Inqui&s;itive about Futurities. Take the Rebuke of GOD; Deut. XXIX. 29. <HI>Secret Things belong unto the Lord our GOD.</HI> Indeed there are &s;ome <HI>Things to come,</HI> whereof we may commendably &amp; profitably be Inqui&s;itive; But they are &s;uch Things as our GOD has <HI>Reveled</HI>
<PB N="15" REF="002913_0017_0FE694F410055D38">unto us, in the Prophecies of our Bible. The&s;e are Things, which <HI>Piety</HI> would make us <HI>De&s;ire to look into.</HI> The Tribe which has <HI>Under&s;tanding in the Times,</HI> is to be applauded for it. They who <HI>De&s;cern not the Signs of the Times,</HI> to be up|braided for it. But what is this, to the Impious and Criminal <HI>Curio&s;ity</HI> of them, who will needs be prying into Faturities, which GOD will have to be concealed from us? I tell you, The <HI>Beth|&s;hemites</HI> might as well pry into the Ark of GOD. For Men to gra&s;p after &s;uch a <HI>Knowledge</HI> of their <HI>Time,</HI> as may indi&s;po&s;e them for a mode&s;t wait|ing upon the Providence of GOD; Verily, 'Tis a great Iniquity. Hence, to con&s;ult <HI>A&s;trologers</HI> and <HI>Fortune-tellers,</HI> about our <HI>Time,</HI> and the E|vents thereof; 'Tis a Crime; As to <HI>Believe</HI> them, 'tis a Weakne&s;s, 'tis a Madne&s;s. Tho&s;e <HI>Propheta&s;ters;</HI> Pittiful <HI>Jugglers</HI> Mankind &s;trangely degrade and di&s;grace them&s;elves, by &s;uffering tho&s;e <HI>Jugglers</HI> to impo&s;e upon them. Indeed, they have no <HI>Rules</HI> worth a &s;traw to go by. If they do any thing to purpo&s;e, 'tis by a <HI>Satanical Impul&s;e.</HI> Their pretended <HI>Rules of Art</HI> are meer cheats. And the wretches them&s;elves u&s;ually have &s;uch <HI>Tragical,</HI> but <HI>Unfore&s;een</HI> Things befalling of them, 'tis marvellous that the credit of the <HI>whole Sect</HI> is not for ever Extingui&s;hed. Indeed, one can't but wonder, as the Roman Ora|tor long ago did about their <HI>Augurs,</HI> how the wretches can look one another in the Face, with|out a &s;cornful &s;neer at the cheats which they a|gree to put upon the <HI>Vast Herd</HI> that pay Regard unto them. <HI>Chri&s;tians,</HI> Indulge not the Vice of
<PB N="16" REF="002913_0018_0FE75E04B9A5EF40">a Mind Curious to <HI>know your Time.</HI> 'Tis a crime, that will ripen People for the puni&s;hments which u&s;e to come upon Sinners, when they have quite <HI>fill'd up the mea&s;ure of their Iniquity.</HI> We have &s;een fearful Examples of Per&s;ons, that have gone to <HI>Forbidden-ways</HI> of coming at the <HI>knowledge of their Time,</HI> and they have never &s;een one Good Day after it. When <HI>Soul</HI> was gone &s;o far, as to con&s;ult a <HI>Witch,</HI> Then the wrath of GOD would bear no longer with him!</P>
<P N="2"><HI>II</HI> WE mu&s;t not <HI>know our Time;</HI> Then 'tis a Folly for us, to <HI>pre&s;ume</HI> upon a <HI>Time,</HI> which our GOD has given us no A&s;&s;urance of. Such is the Folly of them, who pre&s;ume upon an <HI>Hap|py Time,</HI> while they make it a <HI>Time</HI> of Impiety, a <HI>Time</HI> of Impenitence, a <HI>Day of Provocation.</HI> O pre&s;umpteous ones, In all the word of GOD, where have you a promi&s;e of an <HI>Happy Time,</HI> for un|godly People, <HI>going on &s;till in their Tre&s;pa&s;&s;es?</HI> Yea, &s;uch is the Folly of all, who pre&s;ume that their <HI>Time</HI> will always be <HI>ju&s;t what it is.</HI> For Men to Dream that all things will continue <HI>Long unaltered</HI> from what they are at this <HI>Time:</HI> Let me tell you, This. <HI>Dream</HI> is u&s;ually a very dead|ly Symptom. When Men are mo&s;t <HI>Secure,</HI> and are Fearle&s;s of any <HI>Alteration</HI> upon their Circum|&s;tances; Then 'tis, that the Deadlie&s;t <HI>Alterations</HI> are mo&s;t near unto them. An Old Man brags, he is as <HI>Well</HI> and <HI>Strong</HI> as he has been the&s;e <HI>Many Years;</HI> he hopes he &s;hall yet &s;ee <HI>Many Years.</HI> He Dies <HI>this Year!</HI> Oh! Don't fall into a Dead Sleep of <HI>Security.</HI> 'Tis a tremendous
<PB N="17" REF="002913_0019_0FE694F597953370">pa&s;&s;age; [And mark what I tell you, There are whole <HI>Nations</HI> that will VERY QUICKLY have it fulfill'd upon them!] 1 The&s;. V. 3. <HI>When they &s;ay, peace and &s;afety, then &s;udden de|&s;truction cometh.</HI> When and How is a <HI>Bel&s;hazzar</HI> taken off? In&s;tead of a Fooli&s;h <HI>Security</HI> be ever|more <HI>Su&s;picious,</HI> and &s;till Su&s;pect what may happen between the <HI>Cup</HI> and the <HI>Lip,</HI> and with an ea&s;y Frame of Mind Leave all in the Hand of a Glorious GOD ready to take any <HI>Cup</HI> that He &s;hall order for you. Say with an ea&s;y Mind; <HI>I know not my Time; and I am content that I do not know it. But, O my God, I know in my Time nothing will befall me, but what thou ordere&s;t, and I chearfully refer all to thy ordering!</HI> But I will go on, and charge this Folly upon all that pre&s;ume on the <HI>Time to come.</HI> While <HI>Man knoweth not his Time,</HI> thou may&s;t O Man <HI>know</HI> &s;o much of thy <HI>Time,</HI> That the <HI>Pre&s;ent Time</HI> is thy <HI>only Time.</HI> All <HI>Thy Time,</HI> is <HI>This Time.</HI> Do not Rely upon a <HI>To-Morrow,</HI> or upon, <HI>A more convenient Sea&s;on,</HI> for any thing that thou art now to do for the Good of Thy &s;elf or Others O <HI>Do with thy might, what thy Hand find to do.</HI> For <HI>know</HI> this; Thou <HI>knowe&s;t</HI> of no other <HI>Time</HI> for the doing of it.</P>
<P N="3"><HI>III.</HI> WHAT now remains, but this Word of Command, <HI>Make all Ready!</HI> Oh! Let us <HI>make Ready</HI> for whatever <HI>Times</HI> are to pa&s;s over us.</P>
<P><HI>MAKE Ready</HI> for <HI>Changes</HI> of Every Sort. This do by getting into that po&s;ture of Mind, which is de&s;cribed &s;o, P&s;al. CXII. 7. <HI>He &s;hall
<PB N="18" REF="002913_0020_0FE694C12161AF50">not be afraid of evil tidings; His Heart is fixed, tru&s;ting in the Lord.</HI></P>
<P>BUT above all, <HI>Make Ready</HI> for that Greate&s;t and Sureft of all our <HI>Changes;</HI> The DEATH of which I may &s;ay, <HI>The Day is Near, it is near, and it ha&s;tneth greatly!</HI> Indeed, for the animation of all PIETY, this Meditation, <HI>Man knows not his Time;</HI> Tis an In&s;trument of which I may &s;ay, <HI>There is none like it.</HI> How would it come like a <HI>Red-hot Stone</HI> from the <HI>Altar,</HI> to enflame our Devotions, if when we are going to <HI>Prayer,</HI> we &s;hould think, <HI>I know not my Time: This may be the la&s;t Time that ever I &s;hall call upon GOD, before I am fetch'd away to appear before Him!</HI> What <HI>Salt</HI> would it &s;ea&s;on our <HI>Speech</HI> withal, if in our Conver&s;ation with our Friends we &s;hould think, <HI>I know not my Time: This may be the la&s;t Time of my Conver&s;ing with &s;uch as I am now talk|ing to!</HI> At what a rate &s;hould we <HI>Sabbatize,</HI> if upon the Arrival of the <HI>Lords-Day,</HI> we &s;hould think, <HI>I know not my Time: This may be the la&s;t Lords Day that I &s;hall &s;ee before my Dying Day!</HI> But the Grand concern of PIETY, is in that, <HI>Be Ye Ready.</HI> And, My Friends, That you may be <HI>Ready</HI> for the <HI>Death,</HI> whereof you do <HI>not know the Time,</HI> you <HI>do know,</HI> That you mu&s;t be|gin Immediately to <HI>Live unto GOD.</HI> Your Immediate CONVERSION to GOD, This you do <HI>know,</HI> is ab&s;olutely Nece&s;&s;ary; And your coming into His <HI>Covenant,</HI> by con&s;enting that your Great SAVIOUR &s;hould fulfill for you and in you the <HI>Good plea&s;ure of His Goodne&s;s.</HI> By this you make &s;ure of <HI>Grace,</HI> and of <HI>Glory,</HI> and
<PB N="19" REF="002913_0021_0FE694F5B2D71F18">of Every <HI>Good Thing:</HI> and you <HI>lay hold on Eter|nal Life.</HI> This you do <HI>know,</HI> That without this, you have the <HI>Wrath of GOD abiding on you;</HI> If you Dy without this, you <HI>Dy in your Sins;</HI> and you pa&s;s into a World which cannot be without a Shuddering Horror tho't upon! People refu&s;e to <HI>Turn</HI> to GOD, and <HI>Clo&s;e</HI> with CHRIST, and <HI>Fly</HI> from SIN. They do it by <HI>Procrastinating;</HI> By putting off to <HI>Another Time.</HI> O the Phren&s;y of this <HI>Procra&s;tination!</HI> Unadvi&s;ed People, You <HI>know not your time.</HI> And therefore <HI>This</HI> you <HI>know;</HI> This Work mu&s;t not be left undone untill <HI>Another Time.</HI> If your <HI>Time</HI> &s;hould be done, before that <HI>Work</HI> be done, which mu&s;t be done that you may be Reconciled unto GOD, O Mi|&s;erable Ones, you <HI>Peri&s;h Wonderfully!</HI> O Mi&s;er|able Ones, you fall into hands, which it is <HI>a fear|ful Thing to fall into!</HI></P>
<P>THERE once came unto an unhappy Man, that Me&s;&s;age, Jer. XXVIII. 16. <HI>This Year thou &s;halt Dy.</HI> Man, Thou <HI>knowe&s;t not thy Time;</HI> And therefore the Me&s;&s;age may be brought unto thee, <HI>This Year thou may&s;t Dy.</HI> But what if the <HI>Dead Warrant</HI> could be more evidently &s;hown thee, O Thou <HI>Pri&s;oner of the Earth:</HI> And it could be more po&s;itively &s;aid, <HI>This Year thou &s;halt Dy?</HI> Woulde&s;t thou not Immediately Retire to <HI>Con&s;ider thy ways;</HI> Immediately plead the <HI>Sacrifice</HI> of a Glorious CHRIST for the Salvation of thy Soul, the <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> of a Glorious CHRIST, for thy Acceptance with GOD; Immediately give up thy &s;elf unto the Holy SPIRIT of the Lord, and with a mo&s;t flaming Agony entreat Him to
<PB N="20" REF="002913_0022_0FE694C28B3B5DC0">take <HI>Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion</HI> of thee! Oh! then do this Imme|diately, <HI>O all ye People every one of you!</HI> For, O Man, Thou <HI>knowest not thy Time.</HI> There is not one of us, but for ought he knows, he may <HI>Dy</HI> before this <HI>Week</HI> be out: Man, For ought thou <HI>knowe&s;t, This Night thy Soul may be required of thee!</HI></P>
<P>BUT, my Friends, If your <HI>Time,</HI> when it comes find you unprepared, and <HI>alienated from the Life of GOD,</HI> what a Lamentable Condition do you fall into! what amazing Lamentations are you thrown into! The doleful Cry, <HI>Lord, Lord, Open to us!</HI> what will it avail. Twill be <HI>All too Late! All too Late!</HI> But the Horror of &s;uch a Confu&s;ion, O con&s;ider of it before it be <HI>too late.</HI></P>
<P>YEA, Con&s;ider me as now coming to you with a <HI>Me&s;&s;age from the Dead,</HI> and a <HI>Me&s;&s;age</HI> directed more peculiarly and pathetically to the YOUNG PEOPLE among us; and a <HI>Me&s;&s;age</HI> which brings with it a Demand of EARLY PIETY, and their Immediate Conver&s;ion to GOD, and E&s;pou&s;al to their SAVIOUR.</P>
<P>AN <HI>Early Death,</HI> and a very <HI>Sudden</HI> One too, &s;hould never occur, without our Apprehending a <HI>Voice</HI> of the Glorious GOD unto the Survivers in it. Yea, <HI>The Voice of the Lord Cries to the City,</HI> and very particularly to the YOUNG PEOPLE of the City; The Children of <HI>Wi&s;dom</HI> will hearken unto it, and with awakened Souls Lift up their Cries to Heaven upon it; <HI>Oh! That before I am cut down, I may bring forth &s;ome Fruit unto GOD!</HI></P>
<PB N="21" REF="002913_0023_0FE694F98A409688">
<P>THE famous <HI>Waldo,</HI> who&s;e Name has been &s;o con&s;iderable among the <HI>Walden&s;ian Witne&s;&s;es</HI> of our Lord, was brought home to GOD, and made a Prayerful, Watchful, Fruitful Walker with GOD all the re&s;t of his Days, upon his beholding a Young Friend of his fall down <HI>Suddenly Dead</HI> before him. And what? Shall never any more, come to <HI>Think on</HI> their <HI>Ways,</HI> and <HI>make ha&s;te</HI> into a <HI>Walk with GOD,</HI> upon &s;uch an awakening Spectacle!</P>
<P>THO' the <HI>Child Samuel,</HI> were a very Religi|ous Child, and a bright Exemple of EARLY PIETY, we find, that no le&s;s than Three times over, the mo&s;t Holy GOD, from the <HI>Holy of Ho|lies,</HI> call'd unto him, and he was not aware who&s;e <HI>Voice</HI> it was; he was not &s;en&s;ible that there was the <HI>Voice</HI> of GOD in the call. Alas, 'Tis an Error whereto we are all too often liable; and the le&s;s of EARLY PIETY there is in <HI>Young People,</HI> the more liable they are unto it. <HI>Children,</HI> There is a <HI>Voice</HI> to you, in what you have &s;een; and a <HI>Voice</HI> as much directed unto you, as if you were like <HI>Samuel,</HI> by Name called upon: and it is a <HI>Voice</HI> wherein your EARLY PIETY is very audibly &amp; awfully called for. But are you a|ware, who&s;e <HI>Voice</HI> it is? 'Tis the <HI>Voice</HI> of the mo&s;t Glorious GOD, and of a SAVIOUR <HI>wait|ing that He may be Gracious</HI> to you. Oh! Li&s;ten to the <HI>Voice,</HI> An&s;wer to the <HI>Voice;</HI> and &s;ay, <HI>Lord, Speak, for thy Servant hears; and I will be thy Servant: I am Ready to comply with thy whole will in all hearty Obedience!</HI> But what, Oh! what is the <HI>Voice,</HI> to be thus hearkened to! The <HI>Voice</HI> is, <Q>Oh! <HI>Immediately</HI> go thro' the <HI>Proce&s;s
<PB N="22" REF="002913_0024_0FE694C2CBD59A20">of Repentance,</HI> which the <HI>Life of thy Soul</HI> depends upon! The <HI>Voice</HI> is; Oh! <HI>Immediately</HI> by coming into the <HI>Covenant</HI> of GOD get thy <HI>Soul bound up in the Bundle of Life!</HI> The <HI>Voice</HI> is, 'Oh! <HI>Im|mediately Deny all Ungodline&s;s &amp; Worldly Lu&s;ts,</HI> and come into the <HI>Re&s;olutions</HI> of a <HI>Godly</HI> and a <HI>Sober</HI> and a <HI>Righteous Life!</HI> Thou <HI>knowest not</HI> how &s;oon thy <HI>Time</HI> to do the&s;e <HI>Nece&s;&s;ary Things</HI> may be over with thee.</Q></P>
<P>NO doubt, There are many <HI>Young People</HI> a|mong us, who have &s;ome <HI>Convictions</HI> on their Minds, That things are not with them, as they <HI>&s;hould be;</HI> and they mu&s;t no longer continue as they are : Nor are they without &s;ome feeble <HI>Pur|po&s;es, I will not offend any more. Children,</HI> Beware le&s;t you Sin away the&s;e <HI>Convictions,</HI> and a Penal <HI>Blindne&s;s</HI> and <HI>Hardne&s;s</HI> be what you &s;hall there|upon be for ever left unto. We read concerning <HI>Samp&s;on,</HI> That while he was yet in his <HI>Youth,</HI> perhaps a very <HI>Young</HI> Lad; Judg. XIII. 25. <HI>The Spirit of the Lord began to move him at times.</HI> Thus, there are many <HI>Young People,</HI> who feel the <HI>Spirit of the Lord beginning to move them at times;</HI> and they feel Pious <HI>Motions</HI> in their Hearts; They think, They will &s;hake off their <HI>Vain Company;</HI> They will take up the <HI>Religion of the Clo&s;et;</HI> They will prepare for, and approach to, the <HI>Holy Table.</HI> But, Oh! Don't lo&s;e the&s;e <HI>Motions;</HI> and let not the <HI>Spirit of the Lord</HI> be provoked by your contempt of His <HI>Motions</HI> to <HI>Depart</HI> from you. <HI>Wo to them, when I depart from them, &s;aith the Lord!</HI> It was among the Dying words, which the late Eminent Profe&s;&s;or of Theology in the Univer&s;ity of St.
<PB N="23" REF="002913_0025_0FE694F9A5FCEE08"><HI>Andrews,</HI> in <HI>Scotland,</HI> u&s;ed unto one of his Children; <HI>You &s;eem &s;ome-times to have Convictions; Beware how you treat them. They are the most dangerous things that ever you meddled with.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<HI>Mr.</HI> Hald|burton.]</NOTE> Each of them is a Me&s;&s;enger of GOD. If you &s;eek not GOD, and if you de&s;pi&s;e the Me&s;&s;enger of GOD, He will be terribly avenged on you.</HI></P>
<P>IN the <HI>Firmament</HI> of the Sacred Scriptures, what a Terrible Thunderclap is That! Prov I. 28. <HI>They &s;hall &s;eek me Early, and they &s;hall not find me!</HI> Our Ble&s;&s;ed REDEEMER, who is <HI>the Wi&s;dom of GOD,</HI> &s;ays, <HI>They that &s;eek me Early &s;hall find me.</HI> How and why is it then &s;aid, <HI>They &s;hall &s;eek me Early, and they &s;hall not find me!</HI> There is a &s;ad Solution of it. There is the SAVIOUS <HI>Early;</HI> and there is, the SINNERS <HI>Early.</HI> The propo&s;al of the SAVIOUR is, <HI>To Day if thou wilt hear my Voice. Yea, A&s;&s;oon as thou dost hear of me, obey me, and &s;ubmit unto me. Betimes, Quickly, Pre|&s;ently, without any Delay, make a &s;urrender of thy &s;elf and thy All unto me.</HI> But now, the SINNER puts off his cares to <HI>get into the Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> of GOD, until all his <HI>Youth</HI> have been &s;pent in the <HI>way of his own heart,</HI> and <HI>Satan</HI> his had his <HI>Mar|row,</HI> and he begins to feel <HI>De&s;truction coming as a Whirlwind</HI> upon him. <HI>Then</HI> he thinks 'tis <HI>Early</HI> enough to become a <HI>Seeker</HI> of GOD. This, This is the EARLY, which <HI>Mercy</HI> is denied unto. This the <HI>Early,</HI> which the Abu&s;ed <HI>Patience</HI> of GOD will not permit the <HI>Sinner</HI> to find <HI>Mercy</HI> in! You know the con&s;equence. Oh! <HI>Be per|&s;waded, knewing the Terror of the Lord.</HI></P>
<PB N="24" REF="002913_0026_0FE694CB9BE7A188">
<P>BUT I leave the work in the hands of another <HI>Preacher,</HI> and a flaming one. 'Tis a <HI>Preacher</HI> that will go home with you; and there I intreat you <HI>to Hearken unto him, that GOD may hearken unto you another Day.</HI> Let <HI>Con&s;cience</HI> now do its office. I refer the whole I&s;&s;ue to the <HI>Con&s;cience</HI> of the Hearer; and I be&s;eech you, that you would in a due Retirement this very Evening, hear what your <HI>Con&s;ciences</HI> will &s;peak upon this point; <HI>What &s;hould be done by One who does not know his Time, nor know whether he &s;hall have one Day more, to do what he has to do, that he may be Happy to all ETERNITY.</HI></P>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
